children.name: partially c1
children.definition: partially formal if sth partially happens, it does not happen completely or does not include all of sth:một phần
examples: the house was partially destroyed by the explosion.
the ice had partially melted and there was a pool of water on the table.
the advertising campaign was only partially successful.
partial[adjective]
they have asked for a partial lifting of the ban on fur trading.

children.name: partly b1
children.definition: partly to some degree, but not completelyopp wholly:phần nào đó
examples: the poor weather waspartly responsiblefor the crash.
the company’s problems arepartly due tobad management.
the group is funded partly by the government.
the road was partly blocked by a fallen tree.
what he told us was only partly true.
he was educated partly in glasgow and partly in london.
partlybecause
the accident happened partly because we were having an argument in the car.
it ispartly because ofher sick mother that she hasn’t taken the job abroad.

children.name: half b1
children.definition: half
examples: half-eaten/half-finished etcif something is half-eaten, half-finished etc, half of it has been eaten, finished etc:...hết một nửa
▪ there was a half-smoked cigarette in the ashtray.
▪ ‘that’s good,’ he said dully, putting down his half-eaten sandwich.
▪ i found him sitting on his bed, half-dressed.
▪ the houses were half-submerged by the flood water.

children.name: to some extent b2
children.definition: to some extent/to a certain extent/up to a pointb2  use this to say that something is partly true but not completely true: một phần nào đó
examples: ▪ doing well in exams is to some extent a matter of luck.
▪ to a certain extent it was our own fault that we lost the contract.
▪ his figures were correct - up to a point.

children.name: not completely b1
children.definition: not completely/entirelyb2  use this especially to say that you are only partly sure about something or that you only partly agree with or believe something:
examples: không hoàn toàn, chưa hẳn là như vậy
▪ ‘who was he hiding from?’ ‘i’m not completely sure.’
▪ i’m not entirely convinced that we have enough control over schools as it is.
▪ ‘so, is everything clear?’ ‘not entirely.’

children.name: to some degree x
children.definition: to a degree/to some degree formal partly or in a limited way - used especially in discussions and arguments:một phần/đến một mức độ nào đó
examples: the situation has been improved to a degree in recent months.
golding’s novel is to some degree experimental in style.

children.name: in part c2
children.definition: in part formal if sth happens in part because of sth, it is partly caused by it:một phần, phần nàođó
examples: they developed their ideas in part from important work by paykel.
although bad management was the major factor, the firm’s problems were due in part to a fall-off in demand.
his reluctance to help could, in part, be explained by his poor eyesight.

children.name: complete a2
children.definition: complete to make whole or perfect hoàn thành
examples: i only need one more volume to complete the collection.
complete the sentences using either the simple past or present perfect tense of the verbs.
brown lace leggings and black leather shoes completed the outfit.

children.name: make up x
children.definition: make up to complete a group, set, or amount by adding sb/sth to it: hoàn thành
examples: we need two more players to make up the team.
if you haven’t got enough to pay for that, i can make up the difference.

children.name: incomplete x
children.definition: incomplete chưa hoàn thành
examples: ▪ historical records for this time are incomplete.
▪ an incomplete job application
▪ for many, a good meal is incomplete without a fine wine.

children.name: partial b2
children.definition: partial only containing or including part of what is necessary to be complete: không hoàn chỉnh, đại khái, một phần
examples: ▪ from where i was standing, i had a partial view of the house.
▪ this is only a partial solution to the problem.
▪ at best, the mission was a partial success.
▪ wade received only partial compensation for her injuries.

children.name: patchy x
children.definition: patchy if sth is patchy, it does not include enough information, or important details are missing: chắp vá
examples: the records are patchy and incomplete.
a patchy picture began to emerge of what happened that night.
my knowledge of the subject is pretty patchy.

children.name: examining, considering every detail or part
complete b1
children.definition: complete hoàn toàn, toàn bộ
examples: ▪ police made a complete search of the area.
▪ a complete safety check was performed on the aircraft prior to takeoff.
▪ this is a complete list of educational publishers in britain.
completely[adv] b1
▪ he had the engine completely rebuilt. completeness [uncountable noun]
▪ for the sake of completeness we should add these figures to the report.

children.name: thorough b2
children.definition: thorough a thorough search, examination, check etc includes everything that can be included: toàn bộ, triệt để
examples: ▪ congress is demanding a thorough investigation.
▪ have you had a thorough medical check-up within the last year?
▪ his assessment of the situation was quite thorough.
thorough understanding
▪ the position requires a thorough understanding of web page design software.
thoroughly[adv] b2
▪ a teacher must thoroughly understand his or her subject.
thoroughness[u]
▪ the study was carried out with both thoroughness and objectivity.

children.name: full a2
children.definition: full including all the necessary facts, or a lot of details: đầy, đủ
examples: the atlas contains full statistical descriptions of each country.
david wants a full report of the accident first thing in the morning.
lotus will not revealfull detailsuntil the motor show.
full details of the travel arrangements will be published as soon as possible.
the bbc promised afull investigation.
fully[adv] b1
▪ the airline says the complaints will be fully investigated.
▪ schatz pledged that the parents would be fully informed of the inquiry’s findings.

children.name: comprehensive c1
children.definition: comprehensive very thorough, especially because it is important that nothing is left out and that every possible problem is dealt with: toàn diện, triệt để
examples: ▪ the factory was given a comprehensive safety inspection three months ago.
▪ this is the largest and most comprehensive study ever made of the city’s public transportation system.
comprehensively[adv] c1
▪ the service had not been comprehensively reviewed since the seventies.

children.name: exhaustive c1
children.definition: exhaustive so complete that not even the smallest detail or possibility is missed: thấu đáo
examples: ▪ as a result of exhaustive inquiries the police are at last able to issue a description of the murderer.
▪ the list shown here is by no means exhaustive.
exhaustively[adverb]
▪ the report has been exhaustively examined for errors.

children.name: in-depth x
children.definition: in-depth an in-depth study, discussion, report etc is thorough and complete and considers all details: bao hàm, toàn diện
examples: see chapter 6 for an in-depth discussion of this topic.
the study is based on in-depth interviews with a nationally representative sample of 1,500 us households.

children.name: once and for all c2
children.definition: once and for all
examples: completely and in a way that will finally solve a problem
our intention is to destroy their offensive capability once and for all.

children.name: dead c1
children.definition: deadadjective ,adverb
examples: complete(ly)
the conductor waited for deadsilencebefore commencing the performance.
you won't be able to change his mind - he's deadagainstthe plan.
informali'm deadcertaini left my purse on the desk.
informali'm dead (= very) hungry.
informalthe exam was dead (= very)easy.
uk informal"how was the film?" "it was dead good."
the post office is dead (= straight)ahead.
aim for the dead (= exact) centre of the target.
i always try to arrive dead (= exactly)on time.
martha's deadset onhaving (= very much wants to have) a new bike.
he's deadset against(= completely opposed to) living in the city.

children.name: pure b2
children.definition: pureadjectivecomplete
examples: 5. [ before noun ] complete; only
it was pure coincidence/chance that we met.
this last month has been pure hell.
her face had a look of pure delight.
the minister dismissed the newspaper reports as pure speculation.

children.name: complete a2
children.definition: completeto write the information that is needed on a formsyn fill out: hoàn thành, điền đầy đủ
examples: have you completed your application form yet?
in all, more than 650 people completed the questionnaire.
send your completed form to the following address.

children.name: superficial c2
children.definition: superficialadjectivenot complete
examples: 2.usually disapprovingnot complete and involving only the most obvious things : nông cạn, hời hợt, thiển cận
i thought that article was written at a very superficial level.
the documentary's treatment/analysis of the issues was very superficial.
i only have a superficial (= slight) knowledge of french.
superficiallyadverb
the job i've been offered is superficially (= seems to be) attractive/appealing, but i think i might find it boring after a while.
religious education is poorly and superficially taught in most schools.

children.name: with all its parts included and nothing missing
complete b1
children.definition: complete use this to say that sth includes all the parts it should have, with nothing missing: hoàn hảo, trọn vẹn
examples: scientists have unearthed a complete dinosaur skeleton in montana.
complete set
when my grandmother died, i inherited a complete set of dresden china.
the complete works of sbeverything that an author has written công việc hoàn thành của ai đó
we gave vicki the complete works of shakespeare.

children.name: full a2
children.definition: full complete: đầy đủ
examples: sidney got married in full army uniform.
connors made a full confession to the police
the health centre offers afull range ofservices.
please write yourfull nameand address on the form.
please write your full name and address at the top of the form.
the full story
we’re not being told the full story here.

children.name: whole a2
children.definition: whole complete, especially when this is very good, impressive, or unusual: tất cả, trọn vẹn, toàn bộ
examples: i drank a whole bottle of wine by myself.
after spending years piecing together fragments, we now have the whole original manuscript.
i don’t believe she’s telling usthe whole story(= all the facts ).
it was months beforethe whole truthcame out.

children.name: in full b1
children.definition: in full if sth is written, described, explained etc in full, everything necessary is included and nothing is left out; if you pay an amount of money in full, you pay the full amount: đầy đủ
examples: the text of the president’s speech will be published in full in tomorrow’s papers.
the bill had been stamped "paid in full'.
taped testimony will be heard in full at the opening of the trial.

children.name: in its entirety x
children.definition: in its entirety/ˌɪn ɪts ɪnˈtaɪərti/  if something is read, performed, seen etc in its entirety, the whole of it is read etc, especially when it is something very big or complicated:
examples: ▪ bach’s great masterpiece, the mass in b minor, was never performed in its entirety during his lifetime.

children.name: be all there u
children.definition: be all there to be complete with the parts that should be there: tất cả ở đây
examples: ▪ it’s an old set, but you’ll find it’s all there -- the dice, cards, everything.
▪ you can count it if you want to, but it’s all there.
